# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: british-baseball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:british-baseball/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:british-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the years 1845 to 1868 throughout the world.
[src:british-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] At its December 1868 annual meeting, the National Association of Base Ball Players (NABBP) permitted professional clubs.
[src:british-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Twelve existing members did "go pro" and constitute the professional field for 1869.
[src:british-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Marshall Wright publishes 1868 season records for 98 teams, many of them incomplete ("(inc)" in the table).
[src:british-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek calls 15 of that season's teams "major" (not marked).
[src:british-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] This table covers all of those "majors" (not marked), all of the 1869 "pros" (*), all 14 member clubs with at least twelve wins on record, and a few others.
[src:british-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] For the seven listed clubs in Greater New York, no city is named in the first column; the comment gives their locales.
[src:british-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] At least four Association clubs not listed here would someday try professionalism: Riverside of Portsmouth, Ohio (1870); Kekionga of Fort Wayne, Indiana (1871); Middletown of Mansfield, Connecticut (1872); Resolute of Elizabeth, New Jersey (1873).
[src:british-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Meanwhile, only two brand new professional baseball clubs would be established in the next three years, the Chicago White Stockings for 1870 and the Boston Red Stockings for 1871.
[src:british-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Their commercial origins may be related to their survival alone by 1877, and on to 2010, while all of their rivals with older and amateur roots fell away.
[src:british-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Marshall Wright publishes 1867 season records for 89 teams, many of them incomplete ("(inc)" in the table).
[src:british-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek calls 17 of that season's teams "major" (not marked).
[src:british-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] This table covers all of those "majors", all 13 member clubs with at least fourteen wins on record, and a few others.
[src:british-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] For the nine listed clubs in Greater New York, no city is named in the first column; the comment gives their locales.
[src:british-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Star (*) marks ten clubs among twelve who would go pro in 1869.
[src:british-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Excelsior of Chicago and Buckeye of Cincinnati are listed because they were probably the strongest teams in the west after the Cincinnati Red Stockings.
[src:british-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Marshall Wright publishes 1866 season records for 58 of 93 association members, said to be complete for games between two member clubs.
[src:british-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek calls 20 of that season's teams "major" including three old New York rivals of the Knickerbockers.
[src:british-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] This table covers all of those "majors", all 14 members with at least eight wins on record, and a few others.
[src:british-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] For the fifteen listed clubs in Greater New York, no city is named in the first column; the comment gives their locales.
[src:british-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Star (*) marks eight clubs among twelve who would go pro in 1869, three seasons later.
[src:british-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] For the preceding 1865 season Marshall Wright lists 30 members with supposedly complete records for most of them.
[src:british-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Twenty-two of the thirty were in Greater New York.
[src:british-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek calls 19 teams "major" in the first season that he covers: sixteen of the members and three others (Lowell, Harvard, and Camden).
[src:british-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] No one traveled much and membership was still depressed by the Civil War.
[src:british-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] There had been 59 delegates at the March 1860 annual meeting, and 55 at the next annual meeting that December (on a new baseball calendar), who thereby intended to play during the 1861 season that the war curtailed.
[src:british-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Nine of 59 and eleven of 55 were from outside Greater New York.
[src:british-baseball/1890-national-league-of-baseball-of-great-britain] The **1890 National League of Baseball of Great Britain** was the first, and to date only, professional baseball championship for the national baseball title of Great Britain.
[src:british-baseball/1890-national-league-of-baseball-of-great-britain] The National League's headquarters were located at 38 Holborn Viaduct, London.
[src:british-baseball/1890-national-league-of-baseball-of-great-britain] Aston Villa were the National League champions, despite Derby Baseball Club leading the league for much of the season, following their contentious dismissal from the championship, mid-season.
[src:british-baseball/1890-national-league-of-baseball-of-great-britain] Aston Villa were officially known as Birmingham Baseball Club Limited, with their uniforms emblazoned with 'Birmingham AV' on the jersey, despite being officially part of the famous football club.
[src:british-baseball/1890-national-league-of-baseball-of-great-britain] As a result, in some reports of the day, they were referred to as Birmingham.
[src:british-baseball/1890-national-league-of-baseball-of-great-britain] Preston Amateurs were the Amateur League champions, beating Birmingham Amateurs 43–15 and 42–7 in a best of three finals.
[src:british-baseball/1890-national-league-of-baseball-of-great-britain] A large number of leading football and cricket professionals of the era were involved, alongside American professional baseball players.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] The **1938 Amateur World Series** was the inaugural Amateur World Series, the first edition of the tournament that would eventually become the Baseball World Cup.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] Originally known as the **John Moores Cup**, it was contested by the United States and Great Britain over a series of five games from August 13 to 20 in five different cities in England.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] The tournament was won by Great Britain, four games to one.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] Two future Major League Baseball players, Mike "Lefty" Schemer and Mizell "Whitey" Platt, participated in the tournament on the United States team.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] It was Britain's last international gold medal in baseball for 87 years, when the national under-23 team won the 2025 European Under-23 Baseball Championship.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] Mann had first tried to set up a tournament between the national teams of the United States and Japan in 1937, but was prevented by the outbreak of the Second Sino-Japanese War that same year.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] Instead, Mann wrote to John Moores, president of the British National Baseball Association (the precursor to the modern British Baseball Federation) to organize a tournament between the U.S. and Great Britain teams.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] Though baseball was not overwhelmingly popular in Britain, Moores' efforts to develop baseball in Britain had earned the admiration of many prominent American baseball executives, including National League president John Heydler.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] Moores had established a friendly working relationship with the U.S Amateur Baseball Congress (USABC) sent six players across the Atlantic as baseball instructors the year before.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] The USABC held trials for the United States national team in Lincoln, Nebraska, with over fifty young players in attendance.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] England selected their team mostly from the professional Yorkshire-Lancashire League, which in those days was attracting crowds of 10,000 people, though many of the players were Canadian.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] Until the advent of the Canadian Citizenship Act, 1946, Canadians had the status of British subjects and would be eligible to compete for Great Britain.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] The first "test match" was played at Wavertree Stadium in Liverpool on August 13.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] Before a crowd of 10,000, Canadian-born ace Ross Kendrick struck out 16 American batters, out-dueling curveballer Virgil Thompson.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] Britain's Danny Wright hit a home run in the seventh inning; in the eighth, Sam Hanna doubled off of Thompson to knock in Sid Bissett, and Larry Marsh singled to bring in player-manager McNeil for a 3–0 Great Britain win.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] On August 15, the series moved to Old Craven Park in Kingston upon Hull, the home of Hull Kingston Rovers rugby league club.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] The US opened the scoring with two runs from George Binger and Tommy O'Rourke.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] Great Britain's Danny Cadorette scored in the second, and a five-run fifth inning, highlighted by a two-run homer by shortstop Sam Hanna, saw Britain firmly take the lead.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] The U.S. scored two more runs in the seventh and eighth, but a rally in the ninth was cut short when O'Rourke was caught out, leaving two men on base, and delivering Britain the 8–6 win and putting them on the cusp of a series victory.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] The third game of the series was played at Spotland, home of Rochdale A.F.C., and turned out to be the United States' sole victory.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] However, this game attracted only about 1,000 spectators, due to uncertain weather and the lack of Britain's U.S.-born players.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] The U.S. shut out Great Britain 5–0, in a game noted for its defensive plays on the side of the Americans.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] The best-of-five series then moved to The Shay in Halifax, home of Halifax Town Football Club.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] Despite hopes of the biggest crowd to date, the game drew only 5,000 spectators.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] Again, Kendrick shone for the British side, striking out 12 and allowing only three singles.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] McNeil homered in the second to put Britain ahead.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] In the fourth, Hanna walked, Kendrick singled, Cadorette got on base through an error.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] Wright singled to bring home Hanna and Kendrick, then Benson singled to score Cadorette.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] Controversially, the game was called during the ninth inning due to bad light, giving Great Britain the 4–0 win and clinching the title.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] The fifth game of the series was played the next day in Leeds at the Headingley Stadium, the home of Leeds Rugby League Club.
[src:british-baseball/1938-amateur-world-series] The game did not attract much interest, and Britain won 5–3 in six innings, after which the game was called due to rain.
[src:british-baseball/2016-british-baseball-season] The 2016 season was the 87th season of competitive baseball in the United Kingdom.
[src:british-baseball/2016-british-baseball-season] The season began on 3 April 2016 with the opening game of the National Baseball League with all other British Baseball Federation leagues set to begin on 10 April 2016.
[src:british-baseball/2017-british-baseball-season] The 2017 season was the 88th season of competitive baseball in the United Kingdom.
[src:british-baseball/2017-british-baseball-season] The season began on 2 April 2017 and ran until early September.
[src:british-baseball/2017-british-baseball-season] The Triple-A season will consist of 22 games played from 23 April to 20 August, with the playoffs in September.
[src:british-baseball/2017-british-baseball-season] Season will consist of ten rounds from 7 May to 6 August.
[src:british-baseball/2018-british-baseball-season] The 2018 season was the 89th season of competitive baseball in the United Kingdom.
[src:british-baseball/2018-british-baseball-season] The season began in April and ran until early September.
[src:british-baseball/2018-british-baseball-season] London Mets defeated Hertfordshire Falcons in the finals, two games to nil.
[src:british-baseball/2018-british-baseball-season] The British Baseball League is unaffiliated to the British Baseball Federation.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] In the tradition of bat-and-ball games, British baseball has roots going back centuries, and there are references to "baseball" from the beginning of the eighteenth century, and "rounders" from 1828.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] Bat-and-ball games in Britain have a long history and a ball and bat game possibly ancestral to rounders and British baseball was attested as early as 1344.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] A game called "baseball" was attested in 1700 when a vicar in Maidstone decried its playing on a Sunday, and referenced in 1744 in the children's book *A Little Pretty Pocket-Book* where it was called Base-Ball.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] Jane Austen also included a passing reference to the game in *Northanger Abbey*.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] David Block and John Thorn, the official historian for Major League Baseball, speculate that this version of baseball may have involved batters hitting with their hand rather than with a bat, akin to modern-day punchball.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The National Rounders Association were based in Merseyside, England, where in April 1886 they were one of a number of locally based sporting institutions with elected representation onto the directorate of the Liverpool Athletic Grounds Company Ltd.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] Calls were made to follow the success of other working class sports such as football, on Merseyside, and rugby in Wales to adopt a distinct set of rules and bureaucracy.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The National Rounders Association were one of a number of national organisations supported by the National Physical Recreation society, created in 1886 with Herbert Gladstone as President, "to promote physical recreation amongst the working classes".
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The National Rounders Association duly created a new game, drawing on the much older game of rounders but with new rules that they hoped would appeal to adults.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] With plans to spread this new game across the entire United Kingdom, Gloucester adopted the sport in 1887, with the Gloucester Rounders Association formed in 1888.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] In a June 1888 edition of the South Wales Daily News, the now codified rules of this new sport were discussed and it was noted that "the National Rounders Association is the authority".
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] It was also noted that the National Physical Recreation society had supplied a copy of the rules of this new game to the author and "the present mode of playing the game is a great improvement on the old style".
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] In South Wales the game fully took hold in 1889, four clubs were created in South Wales who in 1890 then formed the South Wales Rounders Association.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The rules of the new game, created by the National Rounders Association were as follows.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] "The bases are four, and the runs are made to the right.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] Eleven is the correct number of players, as at cricket, the bowler, man behind batsmen, longstop, one at each of the bases and cover bases.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] A regulation bat, not to exceed 30 inches in length or 3 1/2 inches in breadth, is used instead of the 'timmy'.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] Runs are scored individually to the striker, and collectively to the side; a run for each base that the striker succeeds in reaching without stopping.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The ball must be delivered over the striking base above the knee and below the head to be a 'good ball'; two bad balls count one point to the opposite side.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The threat of the American code of baseball in Britain reached a peak between 1889 and 1890, when a national league for that code was formed, the first fully professional baseball league in Britain.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The National League of Baseball of Great Britain was created at a meeting at the Criterion, London, alongside the establishment a new baseball association, the new association quickly moved to establish a headquarters at 38 Holborn Viaduct, London.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] Curiously the National Rounders Association were represented at the meeting.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] This was the third attempt by American backers to establish their influence over bat and ball games in Britain, in the 1870s, baseball teams from the United States, including the Boston Red Stockings and Philadelphia Athletics, toured the United Kingdom but with limited success.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] In 1889 the wealthy Albert Goodwill Spalding used his position as a former star player of the American code, and as a leading sporting goods supplier, to arrange another tour of the United Kingdom by American baseball stars including the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] In 1892, in “finding there was so much prejudice against the name” the National Rounders Association and the South Wales Rounders Association dropped ‘rounders’ and replaced this with ‘baseball’.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] By the end of the 1892 season, baseball teams from Liverpool and Lancashire were invited to play matches at Cardiff Arms Park with the express purpose of popularising "the improved version of the old-fashioned game of rounders".
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] In May 1892, it was reported that the Gloucestershire Rounders Association had become the Gloucester English Baseball Association, with leagues already under way.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] By June 1892 baseball in Gloucestershire was in full swing, but ultimately this was a short lived enterprise.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The matches would “be played according to the genuine or regular baseball rules”, with a match each in Liverpool and Derby.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] By 1894 the Liverpool and District Baseball League was established and the game was flourishing on Merseyside and parts of Lancashire and South Wales.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] In April 1899, at the annual meeting of the English Baseball Association in Liverpool, it was resolved that the rules of the game would be changed, to speed up play and tackle the “waiting tactics adopted by batsmen”.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The change would see batters face two “good balls” instead of three, and that on the third “good ball” the batter would get an “extra” ball.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] In 1905 the South Wales Baseball Association had just fifteen member clubs, by 1921 the game had become ubiquitous in its heartland cities, with the newly renamed Welsh Baseball Union comprising sixty clubs, all within the Cardiff and Newport areas.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] As the number of amateur clubs expanded in Cardiff, Newport and Merseyside a Wales-England fixture was proposed to promote the sport further.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The inaugural international match was held on 3 August 1908 at the Harlequins Ground in Roath, Cardiff (St Peter's RFC).
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] Wales won the match 122–118 with batsmen and captain Lew Lewis hitting a number of balls 'over the house tops'.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The game in Cardiff had already become a popular summer pursuit among the city's rugby players and the match saw three Cardiff RFC players take the field, including Viv Huzzey, who also represented Wales in rugby union and rugby league.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The next international was held in 1914 at Goodison Park, Liverpool.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The English won the match in front of 4,000 spectators, but annual internationals would not start until after the war.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] During World War I the English Baseball Association were keen on keeping baseball ticking over in the Liverpool region, despite a lack of experienced players.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] In February 1916 the annual meeting was held, with the primary topic of discussion being efforts to utilise munitions workers and others to supplement existing teams, and the English Baseball Association organised games to raise funds for the war effort.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] In August 1918 the English Baseball Association organised an international fixture, whereby England took on Canada at the Police Athletic Ground in the Fairfield area of Liverpool.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] This game was advertised to have been ‘American baseball’.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The game continued to gain popularity during the interwar period and was an "integral part of local culture" in Cardiff and Newport.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] Schoolboy leagues were established, and Cardiff saw the first schoolgirls league.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] In July 1921 there were efforts for the establishment of a National Baseball Council, where members of the English Baseball Association and South Wales Baseball Association met to discuss the formation of the new governing body.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] In March 1922 the first annual meeting of the newly formed Welsh Baseball Union was held at Grange YMCA, succeeding the South Wales Baseball Association.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The new body quickly made a visit to Liverpool and noted that “the closer link formed between the English and Welsh baseball authorities would materially help to attain the standard of a national pastime”.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] Welsh baseball was by now notable for its female participation, which had begun during the First World War among the young women working in factories.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] A women's league was set up in Cardiff in 1922 and in 1926 the first women's international match took place between Wales and England.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] By September 1922 the need for better officiating of games was recognised and the Umpire’s Association was formed.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] In an effort to spread the native baseball rules exhibition games were organised by the English Baseball Association, in London, in 1924.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] Liverpool and Scotland international Donald McKinlay was one of the baseball players on show.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The crowd at the 1924 Cardiff Arms Park men's international reached 10,000 spectators for the first time and the 1925 fixture at the Police Athletic Ground, Liverpool, saw a crowd of 12,000.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] In September 1925 it was reported in the Liverpool Echo that a “revolutionary change in bowling” was being mulled over by the English Baseball Association.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The new proposed rule would be “that when the bowler has sent up the third bad ball before he has sent up the second good ball, the batter shall be allowed to go to the first base, and the batting side shall have a bye recorded in their favour.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] If the first base, at the time, is occupied by another batter, that batter should go to second base.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The Athletic News reported, in June 1927, that a British Cup was being considered, between the finalists of the English Baseball Association and Welsh Baseball Union championships.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] By 1927 the English Baseball Association had three divisions, with a total of 23 clubs across Merseyside and attendances were outstripping those at greyhound racing stadiums.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] A number of international rugby, football and cricket players were taking up the game and Everton and Liverpool football clubs were heavily involved.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] Finally, in May 1929, the rules of the English Baseball Association were copyrighted.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The growth of the international fixture had brought increased scrutiny on the game's arbitration and rules, as such the English Baseball Association and the Welsh Baseball Union formed the International Baseball Board to oversee the internationals in 1927.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] Finally, in May 1929, the rules of the English Baseball Association were copyrighted, emphasising their role in the birth of the codified sport and their governorship of the rules that controlled the game.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The Great Depression saw further increases in the number of clubs and players, and local club matches would attract thousands of spectators as community sports provided a welcome distraction during a turbulent period.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The Cardiff & District League boasted 37 teams by 1929, 19 of which were based in the working class areas of Splott and Grangetown alone.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] In the inter-war years British baseball had a short lived foothold in on the island of Ireland, leading to the formation of an Irish Baseball Union, who organised for a team to travel to Liverpool to play in their first ever international game against England, in June 1933.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] Oswald's, British and Irish, Hibernians, Independent and Connaught ball clubs.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] In the first game, the Scottish defeated the English at Edinburgh by 24 runs to 3, with over 5,000 in attendance.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The return game at Bootle attracted a crowd of over 3,000 spectators, to see Scotland triumph again, 4 runs to 0.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] These two games were played to the American code.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The 1930s saw American baseball's popularity peak again in Britain with professional teams sharing grounds with soccer clubs (10,000 spectators attending the biggest games), and saw the British team winning the inaugural Baseball World Cup in 1938.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The American game was supported by more touring teams from America and Japan; this afforded the Welsh teams a chance to test themselves against the more widely appreciated (and often professional) American teams.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] In one such game on August 27, 1938, the Penylan club side beat the *London Americans* at Cardiff Arms Park.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The contest saw one innings under "Welsh" rules, and three innings under U.S. rules.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The decade also saw further moves to establish American baseball on Merseyside.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The moves met with a mixed reception among players of the British game with some apprehensive the move would end the older game in England.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] Although British baseball would survive, the American league had a detrimental effect throughout the decade, with players, crowds and backers leaving the sport for a professional career in a game gaining support throughout England.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] An American league was also established in Cardiff in 1939, but the professional American game ended with the outbreak of war, and would never regain such widespread popularity.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] Although internationals ceased during wartime, sides would stage successful games with the crews of American warships using either American or Welsh rules.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] Home victories emboldened the local's belief in the ability of the Welsh players.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] This pride and belief was evident when the annual internationals resumed in 1948 at Cardiff's Castle Grounds, with a record 16,000 spectators in attendance and Welsh legend Ted Peterson leading Wales to victory.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] This increasing popularity of the game saw it develop a distinct community appeal.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] In addition to the now established clubs, churches, stores, factories, and bars would form teams, and the game became the heart of social activities for many, especially in Cardiff.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The sport was also enjoying popularity In England, with a number of Exhibition games played in London and teams established in Bristol and Coventry.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The 1950s and 1960s saw more dominance for the Welsh international team.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] Welsh legend Paddy Hennessey made his international debut in the 1957 win over England.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] He would go on to be widely recognised as a great of the game, and the fastest bowler of the era.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The 1964 International saw Hennessey (as captain) demolish his rivals' batting line up for a record six runs in 30 balls and just nine minutes in front of a crowd of 6,000 at the Maindy Stadium.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] This record is notable as it would not be surpassed for 50 years, when Wales international Matthew Hopkins managed the same feat for the loss of just one run in the 2014 fixture at Whiteheads Ground, Newport.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The record remains one of the longest standing in global sports.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The sport gained a new audience in Wales as live coverage of the international fixture and some club matches became a feature of Welsh television in the 1970s and 1980s, but the last decades of the century were generally characterised by a continued decline in attendances and participation.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] In 1989 reserves of the long used worsted made Webber ball were exhausted, following the manufacturer Jaques of London, ceasing production.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] Various American made balls were tried out but found to be heavier and slightly larger than the traditional ball.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The international fixture continued to draw interest with BBC Cymru Wales broadcast highlights of the international game until the 1990s; by then the match was seen as a curiosity with radio and TV features the limit of its national exposure.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The prospect of watching Wales' star rugby players play the game also ended in 1995 with the introduction of professional contracts, ceasing their unsanctioned participation in other sports.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] By 2006 participation levels in England had slumped considerably to a point where only four clubs remained active: All Saints, Anfield, Breckside and Townsend.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The centenary international was held in Cardiff on 19 July 2008, with Wales winning their tenth victory in a row by an innings and 44.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] As well as the full international, similar internationals are held for 'B' teams and for junior grades.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The match was the 83rd international played between the two nations, and was Wales' 61st victory; England had won 20 and two games were declared draws due to inclement weather (1957 and 1998).
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] Spectator numbers were reported to be between 1,000 and 2,000.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The annual England versus Wales fixture continued until 2015 when England withdrew, unable to field enough players.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The end of the international fixture (and the exposure it brought the game) had a dramatic effect on player numbers in Wales.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] By 2017, the Welsh men's league and cup fixtures were abandoned mid-season due to a lack of players at some member clubs.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] Since then the men's game has continued through ad-hoc fixtures.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The women's league remains in operation.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] Subsequent years have seen the Welsh Baseball Union working with local councils to reintroduce the sport into high schools.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] This has seen the sport played beyond its traditional areas (especially the South Wales Valleys), as the game allows for mixed gender participation, is easy to understand, and can be adapted to accommodate a high number of players.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] Among those who achieved fame through their baseball exploits were Ted Peterson, whose international appearances stretched from the 1930s to 1960s, Paddy Hennessey, renowned for his fast bowling, and left-hander Edward "Teddy" Jones whose 1935 run record held for 47 years.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The sport's appeal to winter footballers attracted a number of players more notable for their rugby or soccer careers.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] Welsh Rugby players Viv Huzzey, Terry Holmes, Mark Ring, David Bishop, and Wigan Rugby League legend and record points scorer Jim Sullivan all played the sport, often during rugby's off season.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] Association footballers include Welshmen John Toshack, George Whitcombe, Terry Yorath, Nathan Blake and Phil Dwyer, and Everton and England football star Dixie Dean.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The sport differs in a number of ways from the internationally known game of North American baseball.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The rules today are still very much in line with the rules created by the National Rounders Association, between 1887 and 1888.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] Despite these similarities with cricket, the game is much more like North American baseball in style and operates on a near identical, but smaller, diamond.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] There are also many similarities to rounders, which is often considered a transitional game between cricket and baseball.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The basic concepts of British baseball cross-blend the basic concepts of cricket and the more standard versions of rounders.
[src:british-baseball/british-baseball] The sport is the subject of a song, "The Baseball Song", by the Hennessys, from their album *Cardiff After Dark*.
